    "title": "Unlimited gateway approvals let any compromised allowlisted spender drain proxy-held ERC20 balances",
    "locations": [
      "onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/contracts/RubicProxy.sol:81",
      "onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/rubic-bridge-base/contracts/libraries/SmartApprove.sol:20",
      "onchain_auto/0x3335a88bb18fd3b6824b59af62b50ce494143333/rubic-bridge-base/contracts/BridgeBase.sol:380"
    ],
    "claim": "`routerCall` grants `_gateway` a `type(uint256).max` allowance via `SmartApprove`, and the approval is never reset after the route completes or when the address is later removed from `availableRouters`, so any approved gateway that becomes malicious can pull tokens from the proxy at arbitrary future times.",
    "impact": "A compromised or retired spender can steal all ERC20 balances held by the proxy, including accrued Rubic/integrator fees, accidentally sent tokens, and tokens temporarily parked in the contract during later user flows.",
    "paths": [
      "User executes `routerCall` for token T once; `_gateway` receives a max allowance for T.",
      "At any later time, `_gateway` calls `transferFrom(proxy, attacker, amount)` on token T.",
      "Even if admins later call `removeAvailableRouter(_gateway)`, the stale allowance remains active and the drain still works."
    ]
  },
